  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real concern that I've observed throughout my life, especially when I think about my own experiences and those of my children. Growing up in a small town in Italy, I saw how stereotypes about certain groups—like girls being less capable in math or boys being better at science—could affect people's confidence and performance. When I was younger, I remember teachers sometimes saying things like 'girls aren't good at math,' which made me doubt myself even when I was doing well. Now, as a retired woman who moved to Bologna from a rural area, I've noticed that in many workplaces and schools, people from minority backgrounds or those who don't fit the traditional mold of STEM professionals often feel they don't belong. This isn't just about individual cases; it's a systemic issue that affects everyone who feels they're not 'the right type' for these fields. I believe we should address it because it's harmful and unfair. The key is to create environments where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. For example, in my community, we've started small workshops where people of all ages can explore STEM through hands-on activities without pressure. This helps build confidence and shows that anyone can learn and contribute. It's important to challenge stereotypes early, not just in schools but in everyday conversations too. If we can shift the culture so that people feel valued and supported, then STEM will become more inclusive and beneficial for all. After all, innovation thrives when everyone has a chance to participate.",
